remarks: The southern half of the preserve is closed due to Hurricane Dorian flooding the roads on site (all plots south of Yellow 1 road). Affects ticks and beetles.

Hurricane Ian made landfall on Florida's gulf coast on 9/28 and the eye of the storm crossed over the Disney Wilderness Preserve in Poinciana, FL as a Category 1 Hurricane with sustained winds of 90 mph and 10.10' of rainfall causing flooding in the area.

Nicole made landfall twice in Florida on November 10th south of Vero Beach and northwest of Cedar Key as a Hurricane category 1. Eye of the storm went over Disney Wilderness Preserve. Sustained winds of over 75 mph with gusts of 86 mph.

Hurricane Idalia's eye came ashore in Florida's Big Bend region near Keaton Beach, Florida at 7:45 am on August 30, 2023 with sustained peak winds of 125 mph, as a hurricane category 3. At peak, the Hurricane was a category 4 hurricane. Outer bands as the eye was still in the Gulf of Mexico hit Disney Wilderness Preserve on Tuesday, august 29, afternoon and evening. The eye and strongest gusts of wind traveled north of Disney Wilderness Preserve. Highest projected gusts in Polk and Osceola county which is where the Preserve was located was around 40 mph and 2-3 inches of rain.

Subtropical Storm Alberto caused heavy rain fall, high flow, and flooding of the the Flint River starting 5/25. On 5/30 before conducting an AIS bout, we observed that the buoy had moved approximately 15 to 20 meters downstream of anchored location.

Hurricane Idalia's eye came ashore in Florida's Big Bend region near Keaton Beach, Florida at 7:45 am on August 30, 2023 with sustained peak winds of 125 mph, as a hurricane category 3. At peak, the Hurricane was a category 4 hurricane. Outer bands as the eye was still in the Gulf of Mexico hit Disney Wilderness Preserve on Tuesday, august 29, afternoon and evening. The eye and strongest gusts of wind traveled north of Disney Wilderness Preserve. Highest projected gusts in Polk and Osceola county which is where the Preserve was located was around 40 mph and 2-3 inches of rain.

Snowfall occuring from 11/27/2019 through 12/09/2019 prevented access to tower airshed for PHE protocol for two days and led to damage to several tagged plants on the phenology loop. Additionally, fallen trees are now blocking vehicle access to tower-airshed plots along tower-access road (the tower itself is still accessible). No disruption to access to distributed plots has been noted.

dateRemarks: Flooding and washouts occurred sometime after the 2020 Creek fire, and before vegetation grew back and stabilized the slopes in spring of 2022. Burned areas were still largely bare of vegetation in fall/winter of 2021.
remarks: Areas west and upslope of plot SOAP_002 R (including SOAP_002M and SOAP_006M were burned down to bare soil in the 2020 Creek fire. Vegetation did not regenerate and stabilize the slopes until spring of 2022. This lead to minor flash flooding in the ephemeral creek beds in 2021, and fast moving water deposited a layer of stream sediment in plot SOAP_002 R, primarily in subplots 21 and 39. As of 2022, vegetation is regrowing over the sediment in the flood channels.

dateRemarks: flooding occurred sometime after the 2020 Creek fire, and before vegetation stabilized the slopes in spring of 2022. The area was still largely bare dirt in fall/winter of 2021

Spring time flood water was reported to be nearly chest-deep on the outermost row of the bird grid. Deep flooding was reported on bird grid STEI_033. Report was made by contracted bird technicians so details are limited. Technician reported that springtime flooding created dangerous conditions on the grid and that water that was nearly chest-deep had to be waded to complete the grid. While there quantitative measures of this flooding are lacking, it seems to be more than typical for this time of year so it is being reported.

remarks: Large flood on 8/12/2021. Downstream USGS gauge came in at 7,540 cfs at 6:00 MST. Flow dropped back down under 100 cfs by 23:50 MST that same day. The flood scoured out below S2 leaving them nearly all out of the water. Additionally, the cables to the SONDE and LevelTroll at S1 were ripped apart and the PRT at S1 was snapped in half.

Aggradation of sediment around on-shore staff gauge. Flood stage was exceeded from 2/22/2019-3/16/2019 on the Tombigbee River, which deposited large amounts of sediment at and around the on-shore staff gauge and in-shore staff gauge and sensors.

dateRemarks: Date of rain event and peak floods. High waters persisted after event.
remarks: Heavy rain caused by a 3000 mile long atmospheric river dropped an unprecedented amount of water on a historically deep late-season snowpack causing extensive flooding and road damage throughout Yellowstone National Park. Site inaccessible. roads damaged/destroyed due to flooding. National Park Closed. Will resume sampling when able.
